{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox film | name = Woman at War | image = Woman at War.png | caption = Film poster | director = {{ill|Benedikt Erlingsson|is}} | producer = {{Plainlist| * Benedikt Erlingsson * Carine Leblanc * Marianne Slot }} | writer = {{Plainlist| * Benedikt Erlingsson * Ólafur Egill Egilsson }} | starring = {{Plainlist| * Halldóra Geirharðsdóttir * Davíð Þór Jónsson * Magnús Trygvason Eliasen * Ómar Guðjónsson * [[Jóhann Sigurðarson]] }} | music = Davíð Þór Jónsson | cinematography = Bergsteinn Björgúlfsson | editing = Davíð Alexander Corno | released = {{Film date|2018|05|12|Cannes International Critics' Week|2018|05|22|df=y}} | country = {{Plainlist| * Iceland * France * Ukraine }} | language = {{Plainlist| * Icelandic * Spanish * English * Ukrainian }} | budget = | gross = $1.5 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&wk=2018W27&id=_fKONAFERSTRWO01|title=Kona fer í stríð (Woman at War)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> }} '''''Woman at War''''' ('''''Kona fer í stríð''''') is a 2018 [[international co-production|internationally co-produced]]<ref>http://www.semainedelacritique.com/en/edition/2018/movie/konaferi-stri</ref> [[comedy-drama]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller film]] written, produced and directed by {{ill|Benedikt Erlingsson|is}}, and starring Halldóra Geirharðsdóttir.
Following a premiere at [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]] via the International Critics' Week, it was released on 22 May 2018. It was selected as the Icelandic entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[91st Academy Awards]].<ref name="Iceland">{{cite web|url=https://politeka.net/show-business/736184-film-kotorym-mozhno-gorditsja-ukrainskuju-kinolentu-vydvinuli-na-oskar/ |title=Фильм, которым можно гордиться: украинскую киноленту выдвинули на Оскар |work=Politeka |date=20 September 2018 |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref name="Iceland2">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-iceland-selects-woman-at-war-foreign-language-category-1145754 |title=Oscars: Iceland Selects 'Woman at War' for Foreign-Language Category |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Vladimir |last=Kozlov |date=20 September 2018 |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Abbatescianni, Davide|date=21 September 2018|url=http://www.cineuropa.org/en/newsdetail/360675/ |title=The Guilty enters the Oscars race for Denmark, Woman at War for Iceland|website=Cineuropa|access-date= 21 September 2018}} </ref>.
== Plot == Halla, a choir conductor, wants to disrupt the operations of a [[Rio Tinto Group|Rio Tinto]] aluminium plant in the [[Iceland]]ic highlands. She repeatedly damages pylons and wires to cut their power supply. One day, a long-forgotten application to adopt an orphan child from [[Ukraine]] is approved. At the same time, the government ramps up police and propaganda efforts in order to catch and discredit her. The film revolves around her attempts to reconcile her dangerous and illegal activism with the upcoming adoption.<ref name="Guardian">https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/may/12/woman-at-war-review-benedikt-erlingsson-horses-men-icelandic-drama-pylon</ref><ref name="Variety"/>
==Accolades== ''Woman at War'' was shown at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]], in the International Critics' Week section, where the screenwriters won the SACD award.<ref name="semaine-awards">{{cite web |url=http://cineuropa.org/en/newsdetail/354555/|title=Diamantino comes out on top in the Cannes Critics' Week |date=16 May 2018 |accessdate=17 May 2018 |work=Cineuropa}}</ref>. The film also won the [[Lux prize]] award of the [[European Parliament]] for 2018. <ref>https://luxprize.eu/</ref>
==Reception== Peter Bradshaw, for [[The Guardian]], praised Halldóra Geirharðsdóttir's 'attractive and sympathetic performance' as Halla, and called the overall film a 'well-turned, well-tuned oddity' that was 'confidently and rather stylishly made'.<ref name="Guardian"/>
Jay Weissberg, for [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]], called the film 'a delightful follow-up to ''[[Of Horses and Men]]''', and praised the director for 'arranging beautifully shot picaresque episodes around a central figure who lives the ideals of the heroes she has hanging on her wall, [[Mahatma Gandhi]] and [[Nelson Mandela]]'.<ref name="Variety">https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/woman-at-war-review-1202808656/</ref>
